{:proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:48:02.716969160Z", :proof/falsify-completed? true, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "apm-a01A07-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "WHAT IS REALLY BEING ASKED: {f_n} analytic on Omega, F continuous on Omega, and f_n -> F in L^1 on every disk in Omega. Show: (1) F is analytic, (2) f_n -> F uniformly on compacts, (3) f_n' -> F' uniformly on compacts. This is a rigidity result: L^1 convergence (very weak) of analytic functions implies uniform convergence of all derivatives (very strong). The analytic structure does all the work.\n\nWHY IT IS HARD: The L^1 hypothesis is deliberately weak — in general, L^1 convergence does not imply pointwise convergence, let alone uniform convergence. Students must recognise that the mean value property (MVP) of analytic functions upgrades L^1 control to pointwise control. The continuity of F is essential: without it, the limit could be a non-analytic L^1 function. The derivative convergence follows from Cauchy's integral formula, but students who try to differentiate under the limit sign without justification will lose points."}, :propose {:approach "Use the area MVP: f_n(z) = (1/area(D)) integral_D f_n. Since integral_D |f_n - F| -> 0, f_n(z) -> (1/area(D)) integral_D F = F(z) (the last equality because F is continuous and satisfies MVP — which we prove). Uniform convergence on compacts follows by choosing r uniformly. Derivative convergence by Cauchy formula.", :notes "THE KEY INSIGHT: The area mean value property gives pointwise values from area integrals: f(z_0) = (1/pi*r^2) integral_{D(z_0,r)} f dA. This converts L^1 convergence into pointwise convergence. Then: a continuous function satisfying the area MVP is analytic (converse of MVP). So F is analytic. The derivative convergence is a standard consequence of Cauchy's formula + uniform convergence.\n\nTHE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS: Try to use L^1 convergence directly to get pointwise convergence (fails: L^1 convergence does not imply pointwise convergence in general). Or: try to invoke Weierstrass' theorem (uniform limit of analytic functions is analytic) without first establishing uniform convergence. The MVP is the essential tool that bridges L^1 to uniform."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-a01A07-inline"], :notes "THE CLEAN PROOF:\n\nStep 1: Pointwise convergence and MVP for F. Fix z_0 in Omega and r > 0 with D(z_0,r) compact subset of Omega. By the area MVP for analytic f_n:\n\n  f_n(z_0) = (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_{D(z_0,r)} f_n dA\n\nSo: |f_n(z_0) - (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_D F dA| = |(1/(pi*r^2)) integral_D (f_n - F) dA| <= (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_D |f_n - F| dA -> 0 by hypothesis.\n\nTherefore f_n(z_0) -> (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_D F dA. This limit is independent of n, so it must equal the same value for every r. But F is continuous, so by the Lebesgue differentiation theorem (or directly): (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_D F dA -> F(z_0) as r -> 0. Since the limit of f_n(z_0) does not depend on r, we conclude:\n\n  f_n(z_0) -> F(z_0)  and  F(z_0) = (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_{D(z_0,r)} F dA for every valid r.\n\nThe second equation says F satisfies the area mean value property. A continuous function satisfying the area MVP on a domain is analytic (this is a standard result — the proof uses the fact that the MVP implies F is harmonic in both real and imaginary parts, and a harmonic function satisfying the MVP is smooth).\n\nStep 2: Uniform convergence on compacts. Let K be compact in Omega. Let delta = dist(K, boundary Omega) > 0. Choose 0 < r < delta. Let U = {w : dist(w,K) < r}, a bounded open set with closure in Omega.\n\nFor z in K: |f_n(z) - F(z)| = |(1/(pi*r^2)) integral_{D(z,r)} (f_n - F) dA| <= (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_{D(z,r)} |f_n - F| dA <= (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_U |f_n - F| dA.\n\nThe right side is independent of z and tends to 0 (since U is covered by finitely many disks, and L^1 convergence holds on each). This is the crucial step — the MVP makes the bound UNIFORM over z in K. (This is where most of the work is: the MVP upgrades pointwise to uniform by absorbing the z-dependence into the area integral.)\n\nTherefore sup_{z in K} |f_n(z) - F(z)| <= (1/(pi*r^2)) integral_U |f_n - F| dA -> 0.\n\nStep 3: Derivative convergence. F is analytic (Step 1), so F' exists. By Cauchy's integral formula, for z in K and circle C(z,r/2) (inside U):\n\n  f_n'(z) - F'(z) = (1/(2*pi*i)) integral_{C(z,r/2)} (f_n(w) - F(w))/(w-z)^2 dw.\n\nSo: |f_n'(z) - F'(z)| <= (1/(2*pi)) * (2*pi*r/2) * sup_{|w-z|=r/2} |f_n(w) - F(w)| / (r/2)^2 = (2/r) sup_{|w-z|=r/2} |f_n(w) - F(w)|.\n\nSince {w : dist(w,K) <= r/2} is compact in Omega, Step 2 gives sup_{w in this set} |f_n(w) - F(w)| -> 0. Hence f_n' -> F' uniformly on K. QED."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["proof-a01A07-checked"], :notes "NON-CIRCULARITY: Three independent tools: (i) Area mean value property of analytic functions — standard complex analysis. (ii) Converse MVP: continuous + area MVP implies analytic — standard (proved via harmonicity). (iii) Cauchy integral formula for derivatives. Step 1 uses (i)+(ii). Step 2 uses (i). Step 3 uses (iii)+(Step 2). No circularity: the converse MVP does not use the convergence result.\n\nLEAN DEPENDENCY GRAPH: (1) MVP: f analytic on D(z,r) implies f(z) = (1/pi*r^2) integral_D f — type: AnalyticAt -> integral equality. Likely in Mathlib as `Complex.integral_sub_inv_of_mem_ball` or similar. (2) Converse MVP: continuous + MVP -> analytic. May NOT be in Mathlib. (3) Cauchy integral for derivatives: standard. (4) The uniform convergence argument is a compactness + epsilon argument. Critical path: item (2) is likely the blocker.\n\nNo Lean attempted — the complex analysis API in Mathlib (circle integrals, area MVP, Cauchy formula) is fragmented and the converse MVP may not exist. Design sketch documented."}, :classify {:classification :proved, :rationale "Complete informal proof of all three conclusions (F analytic, f_n -> F uniformly on compacts, f_n' -> F' uniformly on compacts). No Lean — complex analysis MVP/Cauchy infrastructure fragmented in Mathlib.", :notes "CONFIDENCE INVERSION: L^1 convergence is the weakest form of convergence you encounter in analysis. In general it implies NOTHING about pointwise behavior — an L^1-convergent sequence can diverge at every point. But for analytic functions, the MVP acts as a magical regularizer: it converts area integrals (L^1 data) into point values, and the rigidity of analytic functions propagates this to uniform convergence of all derivatives. The gap between L^1 and C^inf is infinite in general but zero for analytic functions. This is a manifestation of elliptic regularity: solutions of the Cauchy-Riemann equations (an elliptic PDE) have interior regularity far exceeding their a priori regularity."}, :integrate {:rationale "All parts proved; no Lean.", :ledger-changes [], :notes "CONNECTIONS: (1) Weierstrass theorem: uniform limit of analytic = analytic. Our result is STRONGER because the convergence hypothesis is only L^1, not uniform. (2) Montel's theorem: locally bounded families of analytic functions are normal (have uniformly convergent subsequences). Our result can be seen as a Montel-type conclusion from an L^1 hypothesis. (3) Elliptic regularity: the Cauchy-Riemann operator is elliptic, so weak solutions are smooth. Our F is a weak (L^1) limit of solutions, hence a solution, hence smooth. (4) The result fails for harmonic functions in dimensions > 2 if you only assume L^1 convergence — you need L^p for p > 1. The 2D case works because harmonic = analytic (up to conjugation).\n\nEXAM-DAY FIELD KIT: (1) Area MVP: f(z_0) = (1/pi*r^2) integral_D f dA for analytic f. (2) This converts L^1 bounds into pointwise bounds: |f(z_0)| <= (1/pi*r^2) ||f||_{L^1(D)}. (3) Converse MVP: continuous + area MVP = analytic. (4) Cauchy derivative formula: f'(z) = (1/2*pi*i) integral f(w)/(w-z)^2 dw gives derivative control from value control. (5) Compact subsets of open sets have positive distance to boundary — use this for the uniform r choice."}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :proved}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T21:48:13.515770030Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:49:25.148321714Z", :cycle/result-status :proved}], :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove a01A07", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01A07", :proof/canonical {:statement "Suppose that $\\{f_n\\}$ is a sequence of analytic functions on a region\n$\\Omega$ and $F$ is a continuous function on $\\Omega$ such that for\nany disk $D\\subset \\Omega$, $\\lim_{n\\rightarrow\n\\infty}\\int_D|f_n(z)-F(z)|dxdy=0$. Show that $F$ is analytic on\n$\\Omega$ and that $f_n\\rightarrow F$ and $f_n'\\rightarrow F'$\nuniformly on compact subsets of $\\Omega$.\n\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "b7a3dcb2857945d436a7fa56ed2c175bea697951c5c707f9a55d06306aabf94a", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Suppose that $\\{f_n\\}$ is a sequence of analytic functions on a region\n$\\Omega$ and $F$ is a continuous function on $\\Omega$ such that for\nany disk $D\\subset \\Omega$, $\\lim_{n\\rightarrow\n\\infty}\\int_D|f_n(z)-F(z)|dxdy=0$. Show that $F$ is analytic on\n$\\Omega$ and that $f_n\\rightarrow F$ and $f_n'\\rightarrow F'$\nuniformly on compact subsets of $\\Omega$.\n\n", :hash "b7a3dcb2857945d436a7fa56ed2c175bea697951c5c707f9a55d06306aabf94a", :changed-at "2026-03-29T21:48:02.716969160Z", :reason "Initial load from APM archive"}]}, :proof/version 0, :proof/tryharder-log [], :proof/failed-routes []}